name: NGSQI
description:
A development environment for the Next Generation Sequencing Quality Initiative Team.

The Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) Quality Initiative offers a foundational, NGS-focused quality management system (QMS) based on the Clinical & Laboratory Standards Institute (CLSI) framework of 12 Quality Systems Essentials (QSEs). Laboratory professionals, including quality managers, microbiologists, bioinformaticians, and others involved with development and implementation of NGS-based tests can find more than 100 ready-to-implement guidance documents, customizable standard operating procedures, and other tools to download and use for free. These tools are designed to be customized by laboratories to meet their specific needs. Find tools to address the many challenges public health and clinical laboratories face in pursuing high-quality results using NGS, whether you are establishing a new QMS or enhancing an existing one.

The NGS Quality Initiative is funded by CDC’s Office of Advanced Molecular Detection, and is co-led by the Division of Laboratory Systems and the Association of Public Health Laboratories.

name: ARXDM
description:
The AR Lab Network supports national testing for antimicrobial resistant bacterial and fungal pathogens across 56 jurisdictions and through 7 regional laboratories. The AR Lab Network conducts diverse antimicrobial resistance testing for many pathogens. Data is reported to CDC ARLN SME groups (DHQP, GC, MDB) through DAART (Data for Action on Antimicrobial Threats) - a system hosted by APHL AIMS. Currently, CDC SME groups experience numerous challenges associated with the use of DAART data, limiting their ability to make near real-time public health decisions. CDC SMEs spend an inordinate amount of time on data wrangling and data cleaning - all using a different stack of tools and technologies - limiting their ability to conduct analysis and generate insights to make these public health decisions. This investment is focused on establishing a transactional data model and moving DAART functionality to CDC while keeping APHL AIMS as a trusted intermediary to ensure connection to PHLs.

The new dataflow will be STLT to APHL (route-no-read) to 1CDP (Redaction, Validation, Transformation) to the EDAV Transactional Database to Programs (DHQP/GC/MDB).

name: NGSQI
description:
A development environment for the Next Generation Sequencing Quality Initiative Team.

The Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) Quality Initiative offers a foundational, NGS-focused quality management system (QMS) based on the Clinical & Laboratory Standards Institute (CLSI) framework of 12 Quality Systems Essentials (QSEs). Laboratory professionals, including quality managers, microbiologists, bioinformaticians, and others involved with development and implementation of NGS-based tests can find more than 100 ready-to-implement guidance documents, customizable standard operating procedures, and other tools to download and use for free. These tools are designed to be customized by laboratories to meet their specific needs. Find tools to address the many challenges public health and clinical laboratories face in pursuing high-quality results using NGS, whether you are establishing a new QMS or enhancing an existing one.

The NGS Quality Initiative is funded by CDC’s Office of Advanced Molecular Detection, and is co-led by the Division of Laboratory Systems and the Association of Public Health Laboratories.

name: NGSQI
description:
A development environment for the Next Generation Sequencing Quality Initiative Team.

The Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) Quality Initiative offers a foundational, NGS-focused quality management system (QMS) based on the Clinical & Laboratory Standards Institute (CLSI) framework of 12 Quality Systems Essentials (QSEs). Laboratory professionals, including quality managers, microbiologists, bioinformaticians, and others involved with development and implementation of NGS-based tests can find more than 100 ready-to-implement guidance documents, customizable standard operating procedures, and other tools to download and use for free. These tools are designed to be customized by laboratories to meet their specific needs. Find tools to address the many challenges public health and clinical laboratories face in pursuing high-quality results using NGS, whether you are establishing a new QMS or enhancing an existing one.

The NGS Quality Initiative is funded by CDC’s Office of Advanced Molecular Detection, and is co-led by the Division of Laboratory Systems and the Association of Public Health Laboratories.

description: Surveillance architecture to receive, display, and send COVID-19 EHR information from Public and Private Health Labs.  The product name is COVID-19 Electronic Lab Reporting System (CELRS).  Data Lake for Ingesting Lab Reports and Admission Discharge Notices (ADT) of different types (HL7 2.x ELR , HL72.x LRI,HL7 2.x ADT FHIR R3/R4 , eCR/CCDA, CSV/XLSX/Flat File)  Processing pipelines that supports receiving data streams from to address multiple ways the data streams are coming in for COVID19 testing. These pipelines then validate structure and vocabularies, transform, translate vocabularies for each of the streams to merge the data into a COVID19 Data Lake. The Data Processing is event driven and make streaming of cleaned merged data across to analytical tools in real time.

name: DNPAO_RAPID
description:
Rapid Analysis of Policy and Program Documents (RAPID) is a web-based tool that optimizes policy surveillance and evaluation by employing advanced artificial intelligence (AI) to automate the analysis of extensive document collections, including state and local policies. RAPID improves the efficiency of document-based research tasks, such as policy surveillance, by leveraging AI. RAPID can be utilized to semantically search through large amounts of documents for relevant material. Users can then ask AI various open-ended questions about chosen subsets of available documents, saving the provided answers and exporting them to further inform their research.
MITRE has developed an Artificial Intelligence powered prototype application, originally referred to as Research Automation Methods for Policy and Program (RAMP), and now named Rapid Analysis of Policy and Program Information from Documentation (RAPID) for the DNPAO division of the CDC NCCDPHP. 
The tool, originally built for DNPAO, has broader appeal and use cases and therefore the DNPAO and OIIRM has asked for this application to be migrated from MITRE’s development sandbox environment to the OCIO NCCDPHP Development environment where Peraton will transition and promote the system to the production environment.
